Later, the "Pope triumphed in obtaining the possession of both Church and State, but there was no period either before or after this beginning of the Reformation when the British christians were entirely exterminated." In short, Thompson, a Methodist, repeated the post-Reformation English dissenter's anti-Catholic view of Christian history. A true, pure, and simple church always existed (even before the Reformation);
18 Ibid., 18, 19, 20.
the Reformation began in England first (with the work of John Wycliffe); and the Anglican Church separated from Rome only jurisdictionally (retaining "the ceremonials which had been fastened upon it by the influences of Rome "). Traditional Protestant anti-Catholicism, then, appears to have been at least as powerful a force in molding Thompson's ideas as American "nationalism."19
